## 📋 Project Summary

Using the **Open University Learning Analytics Dataset (OULAD)**, we built an 
end-to-end machine learning pipeline that processes over **32,000 student records**, 
engineers **15 predictive parameters** across demographic, engagement and assessment 
categories, and produces a reliable prediction of student success in Virtual 
Learning Environments.

---

## 🤖 Model Performance

| Model | Accuracy | F1 Score | AUC-ROC |
|-------|----------|----------|---------|
| Logistic Regression | ~94% | ~0.88 | ~0.86 |
| Random Forest | ~96% | ~0.90 | ~0.89 |
| XGBoost | ~96% | ~0.90 | ~0.89 |
| **Ensemble (Final Model)** | **~90%** | **~0.90** | **~0.96** |

---

## 🚨 Issues Encountered

Issue 1 — Missing values in assessments.csv
  Some final exam dates were missing. We filled them with 0
  (treated as day 0). This may slightly affect late submission
  calculations for final exams.

Issue 2 — Class imbalance
  Approximately 60% of students passed and 40% failed/withdrew.
  This mild imbalance was handled by using stratified splitting.
  If imbalance were severe, we would use SMOTE oversampling.

Issue 3 — Students with zero VLE activity
  Some students had no records in studentVle.csv, meaning their
  click count was 0. These are real values (no engagement),
  not missing data — we kept them as 0.
  
  ---

## 🔍 Key Findings

| # | Finding |
|---|---------|
| 1 | **Early engagement is the strongest predictor** — students with low VLE activity in the first 30 days are at the highest risk of failure |
| 2 | **TMA scores outperform exam scores** as a predictor — continuous assessment reflects sustained understanding better than final exams |
| 3 | **Behaviour predicts better than demographics** — what a student does on the VLE matters far more than who they are |
| 4 | **Late submissions compound risk** — chronic late submissions strongly correlate with eventual withdrawal |
| 5 | **Socioeconomic background has a measurable impact** — students from high-deprivation areas consistently show lower success rates |
| 6 | **Repeat students need targeted plans** — re-enrolling without intervention does not improve outcomes |

---

## 💡 Recommendations

| Priority | Recommendation |
|----------|---------------|
| 🚨 Urgent | Deploy an **early alert system** that flags students with low VLE activity in the first 30 days for immediate tutor outreach |
| 📚 Academic | Shift focus toward **continuous assessment** with timely, detailed feedback over high-stakes final exams |
| 🖥️ Platform | **Diversify VLE content** to encourage engagement across videos, forums, quizzes and interactive resources |
| ⏰ Deadlines | Send **automated reminders** 7 and 3 days before each assessment to reduce late submission patterns |
| 🔄 Retention | Create **personalised re-enrolment plans** for repeat students addressing root causes of previous failure |
| 🤝 Welfare | Establish **dedicated support pathways** for students from high socioeconomic deprivation backgrounds |

---

## 🌍 Real-World Value

This model gives educational organizations a deployable tool to **predict** student 
success before exams occur, **identify** at-risk students weeks before withdrawal, 
and **prioritise** support resources where they will have the greatest impact — 
shifting institutional decision-making from **reactive to proactive**.

